One of the major problems for achieving controllable steering of discrete solitons is the existence of an effective periodic potential, known as the Peierls-Nabarro (PN) potential, that appears as a result of lattice discreteness. While in the continuous case, the presence of translational invariance favors soliton propagation, in a discrete system a minimum impulse is needed to effect soliton motion. The magnitude of the PN potential can be roughly estimated as A4, where A is the soliton amplitude23. We can shed some light into this problem by the use of strongly localized modes (SLMs)24–26. We consider a stationary odd SLM in the form10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
